Buy into a part of a proud Strata Scheme. Unlike many in the area, many of the occupants of 34 Moore are owner occupiers. As a result, major capital works have already been done and some are underway - the future of this strata scheme is one of low maintenance, low interruptions and hence, lower costs.
In it’s recent history, a new driveway and new glass balconies were installed to replace the original. To comply with new Strata Laws, child safe aluminium windows are currently being installed throughout the building and the old windows in this unit (17) have already been replaced.
Equally, the unit itself has had a major rejuvenation since being built and even minor details have been attended to.
Unit 17 is positioned on the third floor, the top floor of the building. It includes an internal Laundry, combined Living and Dining with a generous Balcony, two Bedrooms and Bathroom with shower, bath, toilet and vanity. On the Ground Floor, adjacent to the entry to the building is an undercover car space and storage room. There is also some visitors parking available at the rear of the building.
NBN is available from the Lounge area, and the electricity power board inside the unit has had a complete overhaul in December 2016 to ensure all power points are wired through safety switches. Water efficient water fittings are installed in the bathroom and kitchen.
Only the double brick walls remain from the original build - though, they have been freshly painted. The floors are durable vinyl with 24 years warranty remaining.
Both bedrooms are fitted with large, mirrored built in robes and near new window covers are installed throughout.
Recent bank valuations have placed this unit comfortably above the mid 300’s so this is great value buying in a central location.

Derby is now recognised as one of the best Mountain Bike destinations in the world.
The once sleepy township is struggling to keep up with the demand for accommodation and this demand is set to continue as the number of tracks in planning and construction are completed.
Derby is currently the fastest growing tourist hotspot in Tasmania.
This generously proportioned block of 1920 sq metres is located adjacent to the Tasman Highway, the only road in and out of Derby.
The block is flat to gently sloping with rich well drained soil unlike most of Derby which is built on exposed rock and is expensive or unviable to build on.
The block has approx 2 Ha of Crown land on either side which could be leased now or in the future at a small annual fee.
Behind the block is a vast area of native forest with majestic Eucylpts, towering manferns and massive granite outcrops.
5 minutes walk eastward leads to Valley Ponds, a 5ha lake and wetlands area teaming with platypus ideal for canoeing and swimming.
The Ringarooma River, home to the annual Derby River Derby , is a 5 minute walk to the north.
The block is just 3 minutes drive to the central hub of Derby, offering a convenient escape from the crowds.
This would make an excellent block for Eco pods.
The Zoning is Rural Resources which encourages Tourist Accommodation.
Be quick as Derby properties are selling fast.

A quaint 2 bedroom, 1 bathroom plus study, or 3rd bedroom, logged home with a decent-sized, native-timber verandah overlooking sandstone escarpment and thousands of trees across the valley.
Large corrugated iron machinery shed, secure & stable structure. Chook & wood shed also.
A little logged cabin suitable for guests, visitors or a perfect teenager retreat.
Sustainable
3 rain & spring fed water tanks, 25000, 10000L, and a 5000L self-filling house header tank = 40000LT. About six month's of water storage. Clean mountain valley air, springwater to not only drink but bathe, cook and water the veggies with!
Dam & bore also on the property. Dam has filled & remained full for months at times. Spring (located on neighbouring property) has flowed on the property a few times forming a glorious creek.
Organic veggie patch & organic fruit trees, wild bush tucker & wild medicinal herbs, growing in some of the most fertile valley blacksoil you've ever seen.
Completely off-grid set up, near new 3.5kw (3.5yr old), quality solar array. 36kWh of batteries. Can supply an average of 7kWh/day usable in winter and 12kWh/day in summer. Sinewave inverter can supply up to 3.6kW continuous power. Battery life up to three days of complete overcast. Reasonably efficient new 2.8kW generator (0.5L/hr) and quality 1.2kW battery charger for the handful of times you will need to top up the batteries.
We run dishwashers, air conditioner, kettles & coffee machines. Just not all at once!
Spilt System energy efficient inverter airconditioner has been installed in the main living area. Ceiling fans to main living space & bedroom. A quality woodstove heats the whole house in winter, and with 50 acres of pristine and heavily wooded bush, you'll never want for quality firewood.
Land
50% clear valley floor and 50% bushland with wattles, grevilleas, red, yellow & white box (eucalypt) trees. Plus many, many more. The sandstone escarpment all around is breath-taking.
Bushwalking, rock climbing, cave exploring, hiking. So much wildlife with wombats, birds, kangaroos, wallabies, and wallaroos. It really is like living in a national park, a naturalist and birdwatchers' paradise. The starry nights have to be seen to be believed.
Area
The local people are absolutely wonderful. Everyone looks out for each other in every sense, with regular catchups and neighbourly visits.
This beautiful piece of heaven is located just NE of wine country and 44km by road to Mudgee which is a picturesque country town, with many of the amenities of much larger regional centres and a burgeoning gourmet paradise!
Closer to home is the historic Cooyal Pub. Imagine settling down to a coffee or a countermeal in this quintessential bush pub on the banks of the Cooyal Creek, and in the winter by an open fire!
The local Cooyal Hall has tennis courts, hosts weekly playgroups for families, as well as multiple special events throughout the year, and just built a full undercover playground with bbq and picnic tables for all to use!
Castle Rock, and also Goulburn River & The Drip National Parks, are just some of the magical places to explore & take a dip.
Other Details
Internet available via 25 MBps NBN satellite which has just been doubled in quota to more generous plans. Landline phone.
Waste transfer station is ten minutes away, post is delivered three times a week.
No mobile phone reception or on grid electricity connection available.
Rates are approximately $850 p.a.

Are you tired of living life in the fast lane? Are you looking for a more relaxed lifestyle to bring up the kids? Does a self sufficient eco friendly life sound appealing?
We have the perfect lifestyle property that will change the way you live for the better. This 3 bedroom home is built on 13 acres and is situated on beautiful historic Norfolk Island on the edge of the National Park and will never be built out.
Forget the electricity bills – you’ll never receive one living in this eco friendly house. The house is operated solely on solar electricity. But don’t worry, you still have all the modern cons including dishwasher, gas stove, front loading washing machine and upright fridge and freezer. The 3 bedroom house has an open plan living area plus a pool room or family room.
The kitchen is made from locally produced Norfolk Pine and has stainless steel 2 draw dishwasher, stainless steel gas stove, large pantry and island bench. The house comes fully furnished due to the expense of shipping furniture to and from the island. You name it, it’s included right down to the crockery and cutlery. All you’ll need is your clothes! The house also has a combustion fire, solar hot water and is set up and ready for Pay TV.
The property is classed as freehold and includes 2 water tanks, a veggie patch, tractor and 2 cows. Norfolk Island is only 2 hours from Australia in the South Pacific Ocean. The island lies on the Norfolk Ridge which runs from New Zealand to New Caledonia.
It lies 500 miles SSE of Noumea, 700 miles NW of Auckland, 900 miles east of Brisbane and 1100 miles NE of Sydney. It has a subtropical climate with an average rainfall of 1328mm per year. Lovely summer days range from 24 - 28.4 degrees. Mid-winter temperatures range from 19 - 21 degrees during the day.
The current owners set up the property so that they could be fully self sufficient and it is with regret that they are placing the property on the market. Nestled amidst 5 acres of nature sits this beautiful 2 bedroomed two-storey hardwood timber eco home plus a separate cabin, situated within the Lillifield community, a company title community in the Northern Rivers close to Nimbin. Lillifield is seeking community-minded people who are committed to contributing to community life. Lillifield is a strictly dog and cat free community.
The house is fully off-grid (apart from landline/ADSL broadband) and with established gardens, veggie patch and forest is an absolute retreat. Recently renovated (including wiring) with eco products, it offers a mix of rustic and modern open-plan design, the feature stonework and generous use of timber create a natural feel. For those sensitive to Wi-Fi, there are Ethernet network points in the living area and upper bedroom.
The country-style kitchen is well appointed with granite worktops, a large pantry, dishwasher and stunning stone inglenook housing a woodstove with a baker’s oven and wet back for heating water in winter. With a north-easterly aspect and opening onto a covered deck, the kitchen is light-filled during the winter mornings and afternoons catching stunning sunrises through the valley all year round.
With its elevated position, the deck overlooks a tropical garden and the vista stretches over the treetops with glimpses of Blue Knob across the valley. A peaceful place to relax and observe the abundant wildlife.
The light-filled living room has two large windows with views across the treetops, another brand new wood-fire (to be installed) for the winter months and ample space for sofas, a large dining table and office nook. The hardwood flooring, charming timber staircase and character vintage doors enrich the living space.
Off the living room is the downstairs bedroom which features a stonewall and French doors. The master bedroom is a beautiful loft-style room situated upstairs with a large walk-in wardrobe with linen shelves plus a separate storage cupboard doubling as an additional wardrobe. The timber floor and beams create a rustic feel. This open-plan space also has the potential for conversion into two rooms.
The hallway offers an alternative entrance (if the buyer wishes to complete the small veranda that the downstairs bedroom and bathroom would also open out onto). This gorgeous park like homestead includes a heritage style 4 bedroom homestead as well as a fully functional cottage, built on a stunning green rolling landscape displaying gorgeous views from every angle. The property has been long established in the historic Sandy Flat area in the Northern Rivers, and is close to the booming township of Tenterfield NSW 2372. Embellished in new England style landscaping and horticulture, the property has been carefully planted with deciduous trees and fruiting mulberries to compliment the green pasture and grazing lifestyle. Meandering down the scenic driveway, colours change throughout the seasons as the Liquidambars (sweetgum) turn from green to red signalling the coming winter, the beauty of the farm here really is sensational year round!
Originally a sheep and ram stud, the land has exceptional grazing and is well watered with 7 dams, 3 genuine fresh water springs and seasonal run-off tributaries that course over little rock waterfalls. There are also several rain water tanks, amounting to over 60,000L of rain water storage, with options to increase by adding tanks to the sheds and garage, although owners have stressed the point that they have never run out of water even during the worst droughts.
The property boasts all new main water lines throughout the whole property, bringing water to every paddock to service the needs of animals and installed with the intention of establishing more fruit and nut tree orchards in the fields.
Steel post eco-board and Timber house with Hardwood front and rear decks raised off the ground for Termite proofing and view vantage. The house is fully insulated, very sturdy and well constructed by a licensed builder with over 60 years experience. Country homestead feel with ergonomic design, there is plenty of functional storage throughout the house. Open plan kitchen and living, warmed in winter by a wood stove fireplace with private bedrooms that open each side of the house onto the wide verandahs. Laundry and muck-off room at the rear entry to the house keep muddy feet clean, with additional freezer and storage space. 2 generous master bedrooms at opposite ends of the house make for a very spacious and private living arrangement, complimenting the cozy feel to the home. The entire house has recently been repainted inside and professionally cleaned throughout.
Proven primary production income from the established dog boarding / breeding kennels on the property with annual income as accounted averaging 150k annual. Premises is less than 2 years old and custom designed for low maintenance and to meet the environmental and behavioral needs of dogs. All steel and hardwood design, with lush grass and big iron-bark trees giving shade. If little dogs are not your thing, the area could also be used to keep miniature goats, sheep, ponies or for market gardens etc. Infrastructure cost over 180k to build in 2020, owners are now retiring after many years due to family circumstances changing.
Multiple fully fenced pastures support rotational grazing for cattle (up to 50 head), horses, sheep, donkeys, alpacas and a few families of native wallabies, kangaroo, goanna and echidna. Big old shade trees are spread out nicely in the fields and are home to the occasional koala sighted, while hardwood forest of stringy and iron bark surround the vista. Firebreaks have been maintained along the perimeter, and the Sandy Flat Rural Fire Station is right across the road for an added sense of safety.
Electric front gate allows for easy access when returning home from town, and provides extra security / private access for studio guests. Rustic sandstone pillars greet you when entering the property, with a private entrance right off the New England Hwy. Just 13 minutes to Tenterfield Town, with schools, Coles, arts centre, hardwares, library, cafes, cinema, pizza! Close proximity to the Bluff River, National Parks, walking trails, horse trails and world heritage listed areas.

Thirsty Creek is a medium size cattle station, that can and has carried 230 cattle, however, is currently being run as a Brangus stud.
Weaners regularly top the Gracemere markets and we have sold herd bulls up to $24000 which reflects the country's ability to grow and fatten cattle.
It is located 80km west of Rockhampton and only 62km from the Gracemere saleyards.
Its 1882 ac/762 ha freehold country PMAV in place.
Majority of the country is heavy bottle tree and softwood shrub with the balance being heavy bloodwood.
We are currently growing buffle, greenpanic and crouch grasses.
The property is fenced into 5 main paddocks and 6 small paddocks.
It has 3 excellent bores,and 3 dams watering all paddocks, wihich is an abundance of water.
Thirsty Creek itself, runs through the middle of the property and has been running for the last 2 years.
The house itself is a 5 bedroom a/c high set house, set among lovely tropical gardens.
It has a large shed/workshop and an old hay shed.

Are you looking for a low maintenance rural weekender that has easy 2WD access & comfortable living accommodation? Would you like a lovely sunny aspect with great views, creek frontage and plenty of open area for possibly a horse or two? Preferably with little or nothing more needed to spend to relax and enjoy your time away? Congratulations – you have just found it! With direct access off Upper Yango Creek Rd, only 5kms from the main road, this property features a large, modern colourbond shed that has been transformed into a very comfortable and attractive weekender. Glass sliding doors open onto a 50 sq metre decking and paved area that is bordered by a bushrock garden bed with low maintenance native plants and lovely views over the valley floor. Many properties in the Wollombi area have limited sunlight due to the narrow valleys, but this property captures the first rays of early morning sun right through to the last stages of sunset - a beautiful time to be sitting outside. The walls and pitched ceiling are fully insulated and timber lined which creates an attractive and functional interior. You have a large kitchen with a gas cooktop and electric double wall oven, and plenty of cupboard space and bench tops. Two bedrooms are to the sides of the kitchen and one has built in storage and shelving. The front two thirds provides for a spacious open plan living area. A charming copper plated combustion fireplace sits to one side and provides warmth to the whole building. A dining area in the middle separates this from a lounge area on the other side with satellite Foxtel enabled. Telephone and internet services are also there, which makes it very easy to stay an extra couple of days if you are able to work from home! A rustic, matching building hosts a full bathroom and laundry, with mini orb and timber lined walls and hardwood flooring. A caravan and annexe with a timber floor is situated under a double carport and provides comfortable additional accommodation for the extra family and friends who will no doubt be regular visitors! There is a very large chook yard and house, with automated feeder and water that lasts from one weekend through to the next, so always plenty of farm fresh eggs! A shed for the ride on mower and tools as well as feed bins and extra storage is next to this, and catches water in a tank for the horses. A creek is a truly wonderful feature on a property, and if you walk (or drive) right through the block to the rear there is a beautiful cleared paddock that runs along a picturesque section of creek and is a great spot for secluded picnics or camping around a big winter bonfire.

The property is situated at Curra approximately 20klms north of Gympie. Gympie is a historical gold mining town 167 klms North of Brisbane, a short 67 klms south to beautiful Noosa, 74 klms east to Rainbow Beach and 120 klms north to Hervey Bay. There are plenty of additional choices for your enjoyment. The house sits on a beautiful tree covered 20000 sq metre (5 acre) allotment. The three bedroom home (two with built-ins), has been recently renovated and is in a move in, sit back and relax condition. The open plan kitchen, living and dining area also boasts an air conditioner and for those chilly country winter nights a combustion wood fired heater. No need to worry about those high electricity costs in this home because you are cooking with gas and at the end of your day relax with a soothing hot shower or bath, compliments of a gas hot water system. A spare toilet for those extra visitors. Enjoy the softness of the rainwater drawn from three 5000 gallon tanks. Sit back in the afternoon and enjoy some refreshments on the rear covered paved area, plenty of room here, under the 6 metre x 13 metre covered area and great for the kids in rainy weather. Watch the kangaroos laze about in the back yard. As you drive in the hardstand circular driveway, you notice the landscaped gardens and the peaceful pergola area at the front of the house. Put your car in the single garage or the 6 metre x 6 metre steel shed. Tend to your plants in the fernery and your home grown food in the large semi covered and reticulated vegetable garden. Pick those citrus fruits, bananas and macadamia nuts in the right season. As an added bonus there is council approval to sub-divide the property with all the survey work completed. The approved rear block is 12000 sq metres (3 acres) gently sloping to the dam, with a 110 metre access attached to the block (no easement here). Minor work is required to complete the sub-division. Keep the property as one, build another house for your family or treat the rear block as extra superannuation for the future. This home presents itself in peaceful surrounds and in a manner that allows you to relax, with the further opportunity to reap the rewards from the rear block at a later date. Comfort, peace and security, what more could you want. Opportunity presents itself.

The tourist park consists of 7 acres of manicured parkland with powered and unpowered campsites (and plenty of room to expand), 5 self-contained cabins, 2 amenities blocks, a fenced dam and a new pool. All this is beautifully shaded with over 1000 planted trees. There is also a fully renovated 3 bedroom home as well as a 3 bedroom, self-contained cottage, a large shed (14m x 7m) and a fully automatic Cummins 88 KVA generator. The rest of the land is divided into 2 livestock pasture paddocks and a small piece of forest. There is a current water licence for 9ha of irrigation and a pristine water boar. The entire property is fenced and backs onto the north arm of the Endeavour River and beautiful Endeavour Falls. The perfect business for a family with endless opportunities to improve!

"Exclusive lifestyle property with spectacular views" “Kearra Gardens”, 1262 Urliup Road, Tweed Valley, Australia. Location:
“Kearra Gardens” is located five minutes north of Murwillumbah in the Tweed Valley. 20 minutes south of Coolangatta Airport, 30 minutes north of Byron Bay and 1.5 hours south of Brisbane. The Tweed Valley is a sub-tropical paradise on the Queensland/New South Wales coastal border, and is renowned for its lush rainforest covered slopes and pristine white sand beaches. Home to five World Heritage listed national parks and some of the rarest fauna and flora on earth, the valley has become an oasis on Australia’s fastest developing strip of coastline.
“Kearra Gardens” has spectacular views of Murwillumbah, Mt Warning and the surrounding Tweed Valley that can never be built out or developed. Property: “Kearra Gardens” is 2.434 hectares (6.5 acre) of private sub-tropical rainforest and established landscaped gardens of exotic palms, bromeliads and orchids.
Additional to the main residence is a gate house with an off road bitumen car park at the entrance as well as an 8 bay steel shed/workshop with power and separate entrance.Average annual rainfall on the property of 2 - 2.3m (80-90 inches) per year provides an abundance of rainwater for domestic and garden use.
Council zoning is 1(a) Rural with council approval to run a commercial business.
Residence:An architecturally unique residence, three stories high on seven different levels comprising; 3 double bedrooms with adjoining full size bathrooms, guest room, kitchen, breakfast room, dining room, lounge room, office, library, studio Internal grotto and laundry/toilet Internal living area 284 sqm Decks, patios, covered verandahs External living area 108 sqm Built exclusively of timber and glass supported by thirty six full length hardwood timber logs with a central void. This allows large expanses of glass to be used in the exterior walls to capture the spectacular views of the Tweed Valley.
Seperate 3 car garage near the main residence with power.
Highlights include: incorporation of architectual antiques from around the globepolished vintage pine flooring solid slab rosewood Griffith Tablecraft staircases and stairs with natural edges spotted gum interior paneling cathedral ceilings rising to 6m in the living areas and main bedroomlarge custom built Tasmanian Oak kitchenWhat Sets It Apart?
This is a very unique house and property with it's own powerful identity. It was designed and has been entirely crafted by hand from the finest natural materials available by a craftsman cabinetmaker and myself to create a home that will challenge you to think beyond your dreams.
The surrounding rainforest and gardens have evolved into a sanctuary for wildlife and native birds especially the Black Cockatoos (Kearra is Aboriginal for cockatoo). The environment that has been created at “Kearra Gardens” is one of quiet solitude that gives you the opportunity to relax and think.
“A grand design built by traditional crafts persons”……… Martin Rubenstein

This exceptional property in the heart of the Whyanbeel valley stretches for a kilometre along a crystal-clear creek with multiple swimming spots. The Whyanbeel Valley extends north-westwards from the town of Miallo, just north of Mossman, and is home to many sugar cane farms and other agricultural activities. Whyanbeel Road extends into the valley and this property is located at the very end of this road. The section of Whyanbeel Road that extends along the property runs along High Falls Creek which is fed from the large and impressive mountain range that makes the western border of the Whyanbeel Valley. The majority of the property is on a hillside, including a shack which was formerly used as a residence, and the old walking track to the Daintree village. The property would be ideal for an adventurous family or an eco- resort. The property is approximately 29 ha (71.66 acres)
There are two structures on the property , one can be used as a shed and the other provides a good foundation to build a house or basic dwelling. There is electricity and access to water.
â€¨
Some great features of the property:
*Located in the tourist mecca of tropical north Queensland and near well-known destinations as Port Douglas and Mossman Gorge
*Seclusion
*Freehold title;
*Natural topography provides height and aspect
*This property is one of the largest northern-most freehold land parcels that can be developed in Queensland.
Mossman is the nearest town to this property located in the Whyanbeel Valley, its approximately a 10-15 minute drive.
The town of Mossman is located 75 kilometres north of Cairns. The first sugar cane was grown near Mossman in 1896 and the Mossman sugar mill – the most northerly in Queensland – was opened the following year. Apart from the sugar industry, the surrounding district also raises cattle and produces a wide variety of tropical fruits. A short distance from Mossman is the beautiful Mossman Gorge and there are a number of Bed and Breakfast (B&B) establishments servicing the holiday market, as well as the well-known Voyages Silky Oaks Lodge and Healing Waters Spa, some seven kilometres north-west of Mossman itself, which offers luxury accommodation in a rainforest setting. Also in Mossman itself is The White Cockatoo, the premier nudist resort in far north Queensland which offers 3½ star accommodation. .3 hectares in size and is located at the very end of Whyanbeel Road.
Whilst being the administrative centre of the Douglas Shire, Mossman is overshadowed in size and by reputation by the coastal village of Port Douglas, 20 kilometres south of Mossman. Sharing the same latitude as Tahiti, and just 70 kilometres (or a scenic one-hour drive north of Cairns), lies Port Douglas. Stunningly located on famous Four-Mile Beach, this formerly sleepy fishing village is a secluded tropical paradise nestled between tropical World Heritage Rainforest and the Great Barrier Reef. Port Douglas is renowned for its great range of award-winning restaurants and attractive tree-lined streets bordered with galleries, boutiques and sidewalk cafes.
Easily accessible by car, bus, coach, limousine, boat and helicopter, Port Douglas is the gateway to the Great Barrier Reef and the World Heritage Daintree Rainforest. Port Douglas has long been a popular destination for the well-heeled tourist, with a number of quality resorts such as the Sheraton Mirage, Peppers Links Resort, Radisson Treetops Resort, Outrigger Port Douglas and Rydges Reef Resort. More have just recently been constructed such as Bale’, Juniper’s Sea Temple Resort, and Lagoons @ Port. Sheraton Mirage was recently purchased by a Chinese investor for new renovations. This recent activity along with many of the other attractions of Port Douglas make the property I'm selling very attractive and could potentially be an investors great opportunity to develop a unique business venture. Port Douglas has a number of world-class golf courses and the water temperature is warm enough to swim all year round. Its many attractions include fishing, diving, sailing, white-water rafting, four-wheel driving, horse-riding and even just lazing in the sun. Hidden in the Whyanbeel Valley are a number of executive retreats (villas) set amidst rainforest acres that offer exclusive and luxurious private holiday accommodation.
The land presents a number of development opportunities :
* Potential for a wide range of commercial, tourist and/or residential uses;
*Can appeal to a wide range of markets, e.g. the eco-tourism market
* Lessees of cash crops incur the responsibility for, and costs of, land clearing;
This is very unique rainforest land and I'm willing to negotiate a good price for an interested buyer. I'm available to show the property in more detail at anytime.

This tastefully renovated 3 bedroom brick veneer cottage with uninterrupted views to the North-West's iconic Mount Roland is for sale! Situated in West Kentish, this 1600 m2 plot is sandwiched between pastoral grazing land providing optimum peace and quiet and privacy.
The house welcomes you with a brand new concrete patio at the front of the home. The entry opens to the hall area leading to living spaces, bedrooms and bathroom. With a north-western aspect for the sunny lounge, it is comfortable at all times of year between the natural sunlight and a wood fire for those chilly Tasmanian nights. The lounge is semi open plan which leads into the sunny kitchen area, which has been recently renovated. It has a large pantry, perfect for all your food storage.
Down the hall, the two main bedrooms capture the afternoon sunlight on the western side. Both rooms feature built in robes with plenty of storage space. To the end of the hall is the bathroom which has also been newly renovated, a bright, white space with bath and a separate shower.
The laundry and WC are situated in the middle of the home with an additional room to the back of the house. This could easily be used as a third bedroom but we use it as a music room. This room opens to the back porch.
To the rear of the house off the back porch area is an additional storage room which is perfect for all the odds and ends and camping equipment you may have. It also holds unlocked potential for renovation as it would have perfect views of Mount Roland.
The gardens are easily maintained with most being grassed area. There is a fenced off vegetable garden in the back yard in which we have grown so much delicious produce. There is a chicken coop for your own feathered friends to lay your morning eggs.
There is also a single garage and a garden shed as well as approx 35,000 litre in total of water storage.
This property is situated an easy 5 minute drive from the township of Sheffield which has a kindergarten to grade 10 public school, and the property is a pleasant 30 minutes commute to Devonport.
